================================================================================
                         librjss – Rust JSS Authentication Library
================================================================================

A protocol-agnostic, framework-agnostic Rust library for cookie-based session
authentication. It provides traits for user lookup and session storage, and a
ready-to-use `AuthManager` that ties everything together.

Version   : 0.3.0
License   : MIT
Author    : mroczect <mroczect@proton.me>

----

STATUS
------
Early development – APIs may change without notice.

----

INSTALLATION
------------
Since the library is not published on crates.io yet, add it as a git
dependency in your `Cargo.toml`:

    [dependencies]
    librjss = { git = "https://github.com/mroczect/librjss.git" }

----

PROJECT STRUCTURE
-----------------
The repository is a Cargo workspace containing two members:

    librjss/         The core library
    app/             An example authentication server built with actix-web

Inside `librjss/src`:

    lib.rs                       Root – re-exports api and handler
    api/
      mod.rs                     AuthManager struct
      auth/
        mod.rs                   Re-exports cookies, login, logout, session
        cookies.rs               Cookie creation, parsing, removal
        login.rs                 Login logic
        logout.rs                Logout logic
        session.rs               Session creation, validation, destruction
    handler/
      mod.rs                     Re-exports config, error, session_store, types
      config.rs                  AuthConfig, SameSite, AuthConfigBuilder
      env.rs                     AuthConfig::from_env()
      error.rs                   AuthError enum and helpers
      session_store.rs           MemorySessionStore
      types.rs                   Core data types and traits

----

CORE CONCEPTS
-------------
All authentication flows revolve around three components:

1. AuthManager
   Holds an `AuthConfig`, a `UserProvider`, and a `SessionStore`.
   Provides high-level methods: `login`, `logout`, `validate_session`,
   `create_session`, `destroy_session`.

2. UserProvider (trait)
   You implement this to authenticate users against your database.

3. SessionStore (trait)
   You implement this to persist session data (in-memory, Redis, DB, …).

----

MODULE DOCUMENTATION
--------------------

================================================================================
handler::types   (librjss::handler::types)
================================================================================

All fundamental types and traits are defined here.

Types
-----

SessionId
    A newtype over String that identifies a session.

    Constructors:
        SessionId::new(id: String) -> Self

    Methods:
        .as_str() -> &str

    Traits implemented:
        Display, Clone, PartialEq, Eq, Hash, Serialize, Deserialize

Credentials
    Represents login credentials.

    Fields:
        username: String
        password: String

UserInfo
    Information about an authenticated user.

    Fields:
        user_id: String
        extra: serde_json::Value      Arbitrary extra claims/data.

SessionInfo
    Full session record stored in the SessionStore.

    Fields:
        user_id: String
        data: serde_json::Value       Copied from UserInfo.extra
        issued_at: OffsetDateTime
        expires_at: OffsetDateTime
        idle_deadline: Option<OffsetDateTime>   None if idle timeout disabled

HttpResponse
    A minimal HTTP response, decoupled from any web framework.

    Fields:
        status: http::StatusCode
        headers: Vec<(String, String)>
        body: String

    Constructors:
        HttpResponse::new(status: StatusCode, body: String) -> Self
        HttpResponse::json(status: StatusCode, body: serde_json::Value) -> Self
            (Automatically adds "Content-Type: application/json" header)

    Builder method:
        .with_header(key: String, value: String) -> Self
            Appends a header. Can be chained.

Traits
------

UserProvider (async_trait)
    Must be implemented to supply user authentication.

    async fn authenticate(&self, credentials: &Credentials)
        -> Result<UserInfo, AuthError>
        Authenticate a user with the given credentials.

    async fn get_user_by_id(&self, user_id: &str)
        -> Result<Option<UserInfo>, AuthError>
        Retrieve a user by their unique ID.

SessionStore (async_trait)
    Must be implemented for session persistence.

    async fn save(&self, id: &SessionId, info: &SessionInfo)
        -> Result<(), AuthError>

    async fn load(&self, id: &SessionId)
        -> Result<Option<SessionInfo>, AuthError>

    async fn delete(&self, id: &SessionId)
        -> Result<(), AuthError>

    async fn cleanup(&self)
        -> Result<(), AuthError>
        Remove expired sessions. Called periodically.

================================================================================
handler::config   (librjss::handler::config)
================================================================================

AuthConfig
    Configuration for cookies and session lifetime.

    Fields (with defaults):
        cookie_name:          "sid"
        cookie_path:          "/"
        cookie_domain:        None
        cookie_secure:        true
        cookie_http_only:     true
        cookie_same_site:     SameSite::Lax
        session_lifetime:     24 hours (time::Duration)
        session_idle_timeout: None
        login_url:            None
        logout_redirect_url:  None

    Construction:
        AuthConfig::default()   // all defaults
        AuthConfig::builder()   // returns AuthConfigBuilder

AuthConfigBuilder
    Builder pattern with the following methods (all return Self):

        .cookie_name(name: String)
        .cookie_path(path: String)
        .cookie_domain(domain: String)
        .cookie_secure(secure: bool)
        .cookie_http_only(http_only: bool)
        .cookie_same_site(same_site: SameSite)
        .session_lifetime(lifetime: time::Duration)
        .session_idle_timeout(timeout: time::Duration)
        .login_url(url: String)
        .logout_redirect_url(url: String)

        .build() -> Result<AuthConfig, AuthError>

    Validation performed by `build()`:
        - session_lifetime must be > 0 seconds.
        - cookie_name must not be empty.

SameSite enum
    Variants:
        Strict
        Lax     (default)
        None

    Derives: Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Serialize, Deserialize

================================================================================
handler::env   (librjss::handler::env)
================================================================================

AuthConfig::from_env()
    Reads configuration from environment variables. All variables are
    optional and fall back to the defaults described above.

    Environment variables:

        AUTH_COOKIE_NAME
        AUTH_COOKIE_PATH
        AUTH_COOKIE_DOMAIN
        AUTH_COOKIE_SECURE           ("true" / "false")
        AUTH_COOKIE_HTTP_ONLY        ("true" / "false")
        AUTH_COOKIE_SAME_SITE        ("Strict" / "Lax" / "None", case-insensitive)
        AUTH_SESSION_LIFETIME        (seconds as integer)
        AUTH_SESSION_IDLE_TIMEOUT    (seconds as integer)
        AUTH_LOGIN_URL
        AUTH_LOGOUT_REDIRECT_URL

    Example .env:
        AUTH_COOKIE_NAME=my_sid
        AUTH_SESSION_LIFETIME=7200
        AUTH_COOKIE_SECURE=false

    Returns Result<AuthConfig, AuthError::Config> on invalid values.

================================================================================
handler::error   (librjss::handler::error)
================================================================================

AuthError enum
    Variants:

        Config(String)
            Configuration error. Returns HTTP 500.

        InvalidCredentials
            Wrong username or password. HTTP 401.

        AccountLocked { until: String }
            Account locked until a given time. HTTP 403.

        SessionExpired
            Session has expired (lifetime or idle). HTTP 401.

        SessionNotFound
            Session ID not found in store. HTTP 401.

        Internal(String)
            Unexpected internal error. HTTP 500.

        Serialization(String)
            JSON serialisation/deserialisation error. HTTP 500.

    Methods:
        .status_code() -> http::StatusCode
            Maps the variant to an appropriate HTTP status code.

        .to_json_body() -> serde_json::Value
            Returns { "error": "<display message>" }.

    Traits:
        Display, Debug, Clone, Error (via thiserror)

================================================================================
handler::session_store   (librjss::handler::session_store)
================================================================================

MemorySessionStore
    An in-memory implementation of `SessionStore` backed by
    `tokio::sync::RwLock<HashMap<SessionId, SessionInfo>>`.

    Constructor:
        MemorySessionStore::new() -> Self

    Implements the full `SessionStore` trait.

    Cleanup iterates over all sessions and removes expired ones
    (where `expires_at <= now`). Thread-safe.

================================================================================
api::auth::cookies   (librjss::api::auth::cookies)
================================================================================

These functions are used internally but publicly accessible.

create_session_cookie(session_id: &SessionId, config: &AuthConfig)
    -> cookie::Cookie<'static>
    Builds a cookie with the configured name, path, domain, secure,
    httpOnly, SameSite, and max_age (from session_lifetime).

parse_session_id_from_cookie(cookie_header: &str, config: &AuthConfig)
    -> Option<SessionId>
    Parses a raw Cookie header string and extracts the session ID
    matching `config.cookie_name`. Handles whitespace.

create_removal_cookie(config: &AuthConfig)
    -> cookie::Cookie<'static>
    Returns an empty cookie with max_age=0 to instruct the browser to
    delete the session cookie. Same path/domain/secure/httpOnly.

================================================================================
api::auth::session   (librjss::api::auth::session)
================================================================================

Low-level session operations. Public but usually invoked via AuthManager.

generate_session_id()
    -> SessionId
    32-character alphanumeric random string.

create_session(store: &dyn SessionStore, config: &AuthConfig,
               user_info: &UserInfo)
    -> Result<(SessionId, SessionInfo), AuthError>
    Generates an ID, sets issued_at, expires_at, idle_deadline,
    and saves the session. Returns the ID and the full SessionInfo.

validate_session(store: &dyn SessionStore, config: &AuthConfig,
                 id: &SessionId)
    -> Result<SessionInfo, AuthError>
    Loads the session, checks absolute expiry and idle deadline.
    Automatically deletes expired sessions from the store.
    Returns the SessionInfo if valid.

destroy_session(store: &dyn SessionStore, id: &SessionId)
    -> Result<(), AuthError>
    Deletes the session from the store.

================================================================================
api::AuthManager   (librjss::api::AuthManager)
================================================================================

The main orchestrator. Constructed once and shared across your application
(typically wrapped in an Arc or placed in application state).

Constructor:
    AuthManager::new(
        config: AuthConfig,
        user_provider: Arc<dyn UserProvider>,
        session_store: Arc<dyn SessionStore>,
    ) -> Self

Methods:

    async fn login(&self, credentials: Credentials)
        -> Result<HttpResponse, AuthError>

        Workflow:
          1. Validates that username and password are non-empty.
          2. Calls user_provider.authenticate(credentials).
          3. On success, creates a session via session_store.
          4. Returns an HttpResponse with:
               - Status 200
               - JSON body: {"status":"success","user_id":"..."}
               - Set-Cookie header with the session cookie.

    async fn logout(&self, session_id: Option<&SessionId>)
        -> Result<HttpResponse, AuthError>

        Workflow:
          1. If a session ID is provided, destroys the session.
             (Errors during deletion are logged but do not fail the response.)
          2. Returns an HttpResponse with:
               - If logout_redirect_url is set: 302 Found + Location header
               - Otherwise: 200 OK with {"status":"logged_out"}
               - Set-Cookie header that clears the session cookie (max_age=0).

    async fn validate_session(&self, session_id: &SessionId)
        -> Result<SessionInfo, AuthError>

        Delegates to session::validate_session.

    async fn create_session(&self, user_info: &UserInfo)
        -> Result<(SessionId, SessionInfo), AuthError>

        Delegates to session::create_session.

    async fn destroy_session(&self, session_id: &SessionId)
        -> Result<(), AuthError>

        Delegates to session::destroy_session.

================================================================================
api::auth::login / logout   (low-level handlers)
================================================================================

These functions are what `AuthManager` calls internally. They are also public
if you need them directly:

    login::handle_login(manager: &AuthManager, credentials: Credentials)
        -> Result<HttpResponse, AuthError>

    logout::handle_logout(manager: &AuthManager, session_id: Option<&SessionId>)
        -> Result<HttpResponse, AuthError>

----

COMPLETE USAGE EXAMPLE
----------------------

A step-by-step example using a hardcoded user provider and the in-memory
session store, integrated with actix-web.

1. Implement UserProvider

    use async_trait::async_trait;
    use librjss::handler::types::{Credentials, UserInfo, UserProvider};
    use librjss::handler::error::AuthError;

    pub struct HardcodedUserProvider;

    #[async_trait]
    impl UserProvider for HardcodedUserProvider {
        async fn authenticate(&self, creds: &Credentials) -> Result<UserInfo, AuthError> {
            if creds.username == "admin" && creds.password == "secret" {
                Ok(UserInfo {
                    user_id: "admin".into(),
                    extra: serde_json::json!({"role": "superuser"}),
                })
            } else {
                Err(AuthError::InvalidCredentials)
            }
        }

        async fn get_user_by_id(&self, user_id: &str) -> Result<Option<UserInfo>, AuthError> {
            if user_id == "admin" {
                Ok(Some(UserInfo {
                    user_id: "admin".into(),
                    extra: serde_json::json!({"role": "superuser"}),
                }))
            } else {
                Ok(None)
            }
        }
    }

2. Create the AuthManager

    use std::sync::Arc;
    use librjss::handler::config::AuthConfig;
    use librjss::handler::session_store::MemorySessionStore;
    use librjss::api::AuthManager;

    let config = AuthConfig::builder()
        .cookie_name("sid".into())
        .session_lifetime(time::Duration::hours(2))
        .build()
        .expect("valid config");

    let store = Arc::new(MemorySessionStore::new());
    let user_provider = Arc::new(HardcodedUserProvider);
    let auth_manager = AuthManager::new(config, user_provider, store);

3. Use in an actix-web handler

    use actix_web::{web, HttpRequest, HttpResponse};
    use librjss::api::auth::cookies;
    use librjss::handler::types::Credentials;

    // Login handler
    async fn login_handler(
        state: web::Data<AppState>,
        body: web::Json<LoginRequest>,
    ) -> HttpResponse {
        let creds = Credentials {
            username: body.username.clone(),
            password: body.password.clone(),
        };
        match state.auth_manager.login(creds).await {
            Ok(resp) => convert_response(resp),
            Err(e) => HttpResponse::build(
                actix_web::http::StatusCode::from_u16(e.status_code().as_u16())
                    .unwrap_or(actix_web::http::StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR),
            )
            .json(e.to_json_body()),
        }
    }

    // Helper to convert librjss::HttpResponse -> actix_web::HttpResponse
    fn convert_response(resp: librjss::handler::types::HttpResponse) -> HttpResponse {
        let mut builder = HttpResponse::build(
            actix_web::http::StatusCode::from_u16(resp.status.as_u16())
                .expect("valid status code"),
        );
        for (key, value) in resp.headers {
            builder.insert_header((key.as_str(), value.as_str()));
        }
        builder.body(resp.body)
    }

    // Session check handler
    async fn check_handler(
        state: web::Data<AppState>,
        req: HttpRequest,
    ) -> HttpResponse {
        let cookie_header = req
            .headers()
            .get("Cookie")
            .and_then(|v| v.to_str().ok())
            .unwrap_or("");
        let session_id = cookies::parse_session_id_from_cookie(
            cookie_header,
            &state.auth_manager.config,
        );
        match session_id {
            Some(sid) => match state.auth_manager.validate_session(&sid).await {
                Ok(info) => HttpResponse::Ok().json(info),
                Err(e) => HttpResponse::Unauthorized().json(e.to_json_body()),
            },
            None => HttpResponse::Unauthorized().json(serde_json::json!({"error": "no session"})),
        }
    }

    // AppState definition
    struct AppState {
        auth_manager: AuthManager,
    }

----

ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES REFERENCE
-------------------------------
All environment variables are read by `AuthConfig::from_env()` and by the
example server application.

    AUTH_COOKIE_NAME          (string, default "sid")
    AUTH_COOKIE_PATH          (string, default "/")
    AUTH_COOKIE_DOMAIN        (string, optional)
    AUTH_COOKIE_SECURE        ("true" or "false", default "true")
    AUTH_COOKIE_HTTP_ONLY     ("true" or "false", default "true")
    AUTH_COOKIE_SAME_SITE     ("Strict", "Lax", "None", default "Lax")
    AUTH_SESSION_LIFETIME     (seconds, default 86400 = 24h)
    AUTH_SESSION_IDLE_TIMEOUT (seconds, optional)
    AUTH_LOGIN_URL            (string, optional)
    AUTH_LOGOUT_REDIRECT_URL  (string, optional)

    SERVER_HOST               (string, default "127.0.0.1")
    SERVER_PORT               (u16, default 8080)
    CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS      (comma-separated origins, optional)

----

RUNNING THE AUTH SERVER (app/)
------------------------------
The `app/` directory contains a full actix-web authentication server that uses
`librjss` internally. It supports two run modes.

Development mode (hardcoded users, no external proxy):
    cargo run --bin auth-server -- --dev

    - Uses `admin` / `secret` credentials.
    - CORS is permissive.
    - No external session store.

Production mode (external authentication provider):
    cp .env.example .env   # fill in your configuration
    cargo run --bin auth-server

    - Reads full configuration from environment.
    - Uses `ExternalUserProvider` that forwards login to
      https://app.juragansejati.biz.id and stores the returned cookie.
    - Enables a proxy endpoint that forwards requests to the same host.

Endpoints:

    POST /login
        Body: {"username": "...", "password": "..."}
        Returns session cookie on success.

    GET /check
        Requires session cookie.
        Returns user info if session is valid.

    POST /logout
        Requires session cookie.
        Clears the session.

    GET /proxy/{tail:.*}
        (Production only) Forwards the request to
        https://app.juragansejati.biz.id/{tail} with the stored external cookie.
        Requires a valid session and an existing external session.

----

TESTING
-------
Run all tests (library + integration):
    cargo test --all

The library has comprehensive tests:
    - Unit tests for types, config, error, session store, env parsing, cookies.
    - Integration tests for AuthManager login/logout flows.
    - Tests for session management logic (create, validate, destroy) with mock stores.

Test files are located under `librjss/tests/` and as `#[cfg(test)]` modules inside
source files (e.g., session.rs).

----

CHANGELOG
---------

v0.3.0 (unreleased)

Added
  - Workspace layout with librjss library and app example.
  - Core types: SessionId, Credentials, UserInfo, SessionInfo, HttpResponse.
  - Traits: UserProvider, SessionStore.
  - AuthConfig with builder and defaults; SameSite enum.
  - AuthConfig::from_env() reading 10 environment variables with validation.
  - AuthError enum with status_code() and to_json_body().
  - MemorySessionStore (in-memory, thread-safe).
  - AuthManager with login, logout, validate_session, create_session,
    destroy_session methods.
  - Cookie utilities: create_session_cookie, parse_session_id_from_cookie,
    create_removal_cookie.
  - Session management: generate, create, validate, destroy with idle timeout
    support.
  - Example app (auth-server) with:
      - actix-web server, config, error conversion.
      - /login, /check, /logout, /proxy/{tail} endpoints.
      - HardcodedUserProvider (dev) and ExternalUserProvider (prod).
      - ExternalSessionStore for proxied external cookies.
      - Run mode switch (--dev flag).
  - Comprehensive unit and integration tests for all modules.
  - Dependencies: thiserror, tracing, serde, serde_json, cookie, rand, time,
    http, async-trait, hex, tokio.

Changed
  - Entire library restructured from flat layout to api/handler modular
    architecture.
  - Replaced old monolithic tests with focused unit tests under tests/.
  - Removed unused re-exports and cleaned imports across the codebase.
  - Updated cookie creation to use `.build()` instead of deprecated `.finish()`.
  - Locked down tokio feature flags to "full" for simplicity.

Fixed
  - Environment test isolation using a global mutex to avoid race conditions.
  - Internal error JSON assertion corrected in tests.

